        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Restaurant Fire Safety Requirements in Scottsdale, AZ: What Every Operator Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">Scottsdale's Old Town entertainment district, Fashion Square luxury retail, and extensive luxury resort restaurant operations make it one of Arizona's most active restaurant fire safety compliance environments. Here's what every Scottsdale restaurant and resort food service operator needs to know about NFPA 96 and Arizona Fire Code requirements.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">NFPA 96 Kitchen Suppression Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">All commercial cooking operations in Scottsdale producing grease-laden vapors must install and maintain an automatic wet chemical fire suppression system under NFPA 96. This applies to restaurants, bars with food service, hotel kitchens, and corporate cafeterias. Scottsdale's restaurant compliance landscape is anchored by Old Town's dense restaurant and bar concentration, the Kierland Commons and Fashion Square dining operations, and the resort corridor's extensive banquet and catering kitchens. Luxury resort properties with multiple restaurant outlets, banquet facilities, and catering operations create multi-system compliance obligations requiring coordination across all kitchen areas.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Semi-Annual Inspection Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires kitchen suppression systems to be inspected and serviced semi-annually — twice per year — by a licensed contractor. Records must be maintained on-site and available for Scottsdale Fire Department inspection. Semi-annual means every six months from the last inspection date, not twice per calendar year.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Hood Cleaning Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">NFPA 96 requires hood cleaning at intervals based on cooking volume: quarterly for high-volume operations (solid fuel cooking, charbroiling, wok cooking, high-volume fryers), semi-annually for moderate volume, annually for low-volume like pizza ovens. Hood cleaning records must be maintained on-site.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Class K Fire Extinguisher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">A Class K extinguisher must be within 30 feet of all cooking surfaces producing grease-laden vapors. Class K units are specifically designed for cooking oil fires — standard ABC dry chemical is not an adequate substitute. Class K units require annual inspection alongside other extinguishers.</p>
